{
  "updated_summary": "NVIDIA CEO Jensen Huang, clad in his signature black leather jacket, black shirt, black pants, and white sneakers, stood on a dark, minimalist stage, holding a small black remote. He introduced NVIDIA Inference Microservice (NIM), a pre-trained model packaged in a digital container and optimized for NVIDIA's extensive installed base, which he described as a 'digital box.' The presentation shifted to a full-screen graphic of the 'NVIDIA INFERENCE MICROSERVICE,' a green hexagonal icon, and then to a detailed technical diagram illustrating its architecture. Huang explained that NIM includes pre-trained, state-of-the-art, open-source models with all dependencies like CUDA, cuDNN, TensorRT LLM, and Triton Inference Server, optimized for single or multi-GPU configurations. The diagram showed a layered stack with CUDA and Kubernetes at the base, supporting the microservice with industry-standard APIs, cloud-native components, enterprise management, and optimized models, all built upon millions of CUDA GPUs. Huang further elaborated on AI APIs as simple interfaces, envisioning a future 'human' AI with a simple API, and stated these software packages would be downloadable and runnable across clouds, data centers, or workstations, as a large, dimly lit audience watched attentively. He then directed viewers to ai.nvidia.com for NIMs, showing a user interface for 'Top Open Foundation Models' with a dog image example, prompting enthusiastic applause. Huang discussed integrating 'chatbots' into NIMs for future software development, where 'a team of AIs' could assemble software. A complex technical diagram of an AI agent architecture appeared, featuring a central 'Plan' block, illustrating how a 'Super AI' breaks down missions into execution plans, potentially handing off tasks to other NIMs for system interaction (like SAP or Service Now) or calculation, linking to vector databases, structured data, and knowledge graphs. He emphasized that AI agents, using tools like 'Pandas,' know 'what right answers to produce' and can generate daily reports, with NIMs working together as a team on NVIDIA GPUs in data centers or the cloud. Huang also presented 'chip designer chatbots' and 'AI co-pilots' as co-designers, demonstrating a prompt-response interface with 'NVIDIA ChipNeMo Llama 2 70B Before Fine-Tuning' answering a query about Combinational Timing Logic (CTL), though he noted the initial answer was 'completely wrong,' highlighting the need for fine-tuning. He then showcased 'NeMo Microservices' with components for curating, customizing, evaluating, and guarding AI models, feeding into a 'Custom Model in NIM.' Huang outlined NVIDIA's three pillars: inventing AI technology, creating tools to modify it, and providing infrastructure for fine-tuning and deployment via DGX Cloud or on-premise options, positioning NVIDIA as an 'AI foundry.' The presentation evolved to a 'Vector Database' diagram with RAPIDS cuVS Accelerated Indexing and Accelerated NN Search, connected to Embedding, Retrieval, and Text-to-SQL Microservices, feeding into a 'Plan' block. Huang explained how proprietary data is encoded into a vector database, creating an 'AI database' that users can 'chat to,' demonstrating with a 'Chat with PDF' interface that handled multi-modality data and cited NVIDIA T4 and H100 performance. He introduced 'NeMo Retriever' as a system to quickly retrieve information upon request, exemplified by a software team querying a 'bugs database,' humorously noting the need for therapy afterward before introducing 'another chatbot.'"
